1. Using Docker, we can use a textfile common named "requirements.txt" on the root of every proyect
and with the command "RUN pip3 install -r <textfile name>", Docker installes
the version that you put in the textfile with the sintaxis: <library>==<version> example: Flask==0.12

2. I think all the objects and definitions that the requested objects need are loaded at runtime,
because the objects canÂ´t run without it's own dependencies or definitions.

3. Nop

4. It differentiates the part of the code that must be executed when the program is called by an import or
if it is called as the main program.
It is executed when the python interpreter reads the code to execute.